Now that everything is going back to normal, I would like to announce a new update to the validation code: `version 2.0.1`. We have fixed a couple of bugs in the validator code that affects the *Pareto Optimal* line and the winners of the subnet. The majority of the winners will remain the same with slight changes.

Here are the key updates:
1) **Weight Resetting on Validator:** We added new functions to ensure that when we have a winning candidate for the model, we reset all the weights of the layers. This prevents any leakage of information from the trained model, which was a potential issue in the current validator version.

2)** Image Augmentation Bug Fix:** As you know, we apply multiple augmentation methods to the dataset to prevent overfitting. However, the order of these augmentations was incorrect and has been fixed in the current version.

3) **Reward Bug:** There was a certain scenario where a miner might have been rewarded (reward=True) even if they were not Pareto optimal (pareto=True). This bug is fixed in the current version.

**We are asking all validators to update to version 2.0.1. Validators on version 2.0.0 will no longer be able to set weights. Additionally, all validators must remove the state file located at `state/state.csv` before running the new validator code.**

If you are curious to see what the Pareto line looks like under new update now, you can use our validator's WandB to check if your model is still winning under the new update.

**Dear @deleted-role  Comrades,
Upcoming updates to the NASChain Incentive mechanism:**

1) **Simplification of Accuracy Values**: We are removing decimal points in accuracy calculations. For instance, models with values such as 91.8 and 91.1 will now be floored to 91. This ensures that miners focus on making significant improvements to the Pareto front, rather than competing over fractional points. This adjustment will also aid in achieving better consensus among validators using different GPU architectures, as slight variations in results due to different GPUs can be minimized.

2) **Rounding Parameter Numbers:** Parameter values such as 13,560 and 13,900 will now round up to 13k. This means that a meaningful reduction in parameters is required to replace a UID on the Pareto optimal line.

3) **Adding a Third Objective - FLOPs:** We are introducing the number of floating-point operations (FLOPs), in millions (rounded to the nearest million), as a third objective. This defines the latency of the model for inference. This change will transform the Pareto optimal line from a 2D line to a 3D surface. Winning models will now be represented not just as points on a line, but as points on a surface. This will complicate the visualization of the Pareto front in WandB, and we may need to rely on a leaderboard table to present numbers and winners. However, this addition will reward those who can design models with better latency or better parameters or both.

4) **Incentive Scaling Along the Pareto Line: **Incentives will now increase exponentially from the lower to the higher end of the Pareto line. In the current system, everyone on the Pareto front receives an equal share of the mining rewards. The new approach will provide smaller incentives to UIDs in the 80% area than 95% area of the Pareto front, encouraging miners to not settle in this range and instead strive to maximize accuracy.

I will be pushing the update on Monday, and I would like to give miners some time to monitor and understand the new incentive mechanism at the following Weights & Biases link: https://wandb.ai/naschain/naschain-pareto/runs/5DhHWS4CwAdmMFJfGyXuKfJZ3VRrDCApt9eoC2A6HsYyCwdb .

The impact factors are currently ranked from high to low as follows: 1 for accuracy, 0.5 for flops, and 0.25 for parameters.
